<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[317,1270,436,1812]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
– Described from 
<collectingRegion box="[1016,1107,1128,1149]" country="Russia" name="Buryatiya" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Buryatiya</collectingRegion>
of Asiatic 
<collectingCountry box="[1208,1270,1128,1149]" name="Russia" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Russia</collectingCountry>
on the basis of 
<specimenCount box="[453,538,1156,1177]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="male">two male</specimenCount>
specimens (female unknown) (
<bibRefCitation author="BELOKOBYLSKIJ, S. A." box="[825,1075,1156,1177]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="163 - 298" refId="ref22378" refString="BELOKOBYLSKIJ, S. A. (1998) Tribe Alysiini. In: Key to the Insects of Russian Far East. Vol. IV. Neuropteroidea, Mecoptera, Hymenoptera, Pt. 3: 163 - 298. [In Russian]" type="book chapter" year="1998">BELOKOBYLSKIJ 1998: 279</bibRefCitation>
). New to the fauna of 
<collectingCountry box="[317,376,1185,1206]" name="South Korea" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Korea</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[317,1270,436,1812]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
– The two Korean males match the description; deviating features: (1) antenna with 31 (
<quantity box="[1190,1224,1185,1207]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="m" value="1.0">1 ♂</quantity>
) and 32 (
<quantity box="[354,386,1214,1236]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="m" value="1.0">1 ♂</quantity>
) antennomeres; (2) fore wing: 
<emphasis box="[663,672,1214,1235]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">r</emphasis>
very short, one-fifth as long as 
<emphasis box="[953,1002,1214,1235]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">3–SR</emphasis>
; (3) hind femur 6.6–6.8 times as long as broad distally; (4) tegula yellow, tergites 2–3 reddish to rusty.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
